<DOC><DOCNO> AP890731-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 1537EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-FreedHostages     07-31 0398</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Freed Hostages,0404</SECOND><HEAD>Since 1984, Five American Hostages Have Been Freed</HEAD><HEAD>With Hostages Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Besides eight Americans still heldhostage and at least two who were killed, five other Americans werekidnapped in Lebanon over the past 5{ years and eventually gainedtheir freedom.   Here is a brief review:   _Frank Regier, an engineering professor at the AmericanUniversity of Beirut, was abducted Feb. 10, 1984, near the westBeirut campus. On April 15, 1984, he and another kidnap victim,Christian Joubert, a French housing specialist, were freed. Membersof Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia said they had rescued the pair,but the circumstances of their release and the identity of theircaptors were never made clear.   _Jeremy Levin, Beirut bureau chief for Cable News Network, waskidnapped March 7, 1984, as he walked to work in west Beirut. Thepro-Iranian group Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility. On Feb. 14,1985, Levin turned up in Damascus, Syria, and said he had escapedfrom solitary confinement in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley. ButIslamic Jihad asserted it actually had released the TVcorrespondent.   _Presbyterian pastor Benjamin Weir was kidnapped May 8, 1984, ona west Beirut street. On Sept. 9, 1985, Weir was freed by hisIslamic Jihad captors, bearing a message calling for urgent U.S.action to meet demands for the release of 17 Islamic Jihad comradesjailed in Kuwait for the December 1983 bombing of the U.S. andFrench embassies there.   _The Rev. Lawrence Jenco, a Roman Catholic priest, was abductedfrom his car in Beirut on Jan. 8, 1985. He was released by IslamicJihad on July 26, 1986, bringing with him a videotape in whichfellow hostage David P. Jacobsen appealed for the U.S. governmentto negotiate with the kidnappers.   _David P. Jacobsen, American director of American UniversityHospital, was kidnapped May 28, 1985, as he walked to work in westBeirut. He was released by Islamic Jihad on Nov. 2, 1986.Jacobsen's release led to disclosures that the Reaganadministration had been negotiating for the hostages' freedom andhad arranged secret arms shipments to Iran, a development thatprovoked a political storm in Washington that became known as theIran-Contra affair.   In addition, over the past 5{ years at least 34 otherforeigners, including French, West German and British nationals,have been kidnapped in Lebanon and either were freed, escaped orwere rescued.</TEXT></DOC>